                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1011½: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName corresp="#p_GHS1"
                            type="to">Gibson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-30T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 30, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>93. For the Secretary. I have read your telegram No. 161 to the President, who is
                    at the Rapidan. He says that there is nothing at present here which demands your
                    immediate return and feels that if there is “the remotest chance that your
                    presence in Geneva at the time of the conversations might assist in bringing a
                    solution you would be wise to remain”. The President, of course, leaves the
                    decision to you, but feels that an agreement in Geneva is so important that you
                    may prefer to remain, knowing that there is no question here which demands your
                    attention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
